Halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}(peeled and thinly sliced). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1}(peeled and grated) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tbsp} in a #medium saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting #lid{}) on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the red onion and cook, stirring occasionally, until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}.

Stir in the @korma curry paste{50%g} and half the garlic, then cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Stir the @basmati rice{150%g}, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and @water{300%ml} into the onion pan and bring to the boil.

Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While the rice cooks, trim the @green beans{80%g}(trimmed and cut into thirds) and cut into thirds.

Zest and halve the @lime{1/2}(zested and halved).

When the rice has 10 mins left, heat a drizzle of oil in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the green beans and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir-fry until starting to char, ~{3-4%minutes}.

Meanwhile, drain the @king prawns{300%g}(drained).

Once the beans are charred, add the prawns to the pan and stir-fry for ~{3-4%minutes}.

Stir in the remaining garlic and cook for ~{1%minute} more, then remove from the heat.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns. They're cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the rice is cooked, fluff it up with a #fork{} and stir through the @mango chutney{40%g}. Add the rice, lime zest and a squeeze of lime juice to the prawn pan. Stir together until combined.

Taste and add salt, pepper and more lime juice if needed.

Spoon the prawn pilaf into #bowls{}, then top with a dollop of @low fat natural yoghurt{75%g}.

Cut the remaining lime into wedges and serve alongside for squeezing over.

Enjoy!